    "content": "Our solar system formed about 4.6 billion years ago from a giant cloud of gas and dust. At its center sits the Sun, a yellow dwarf star that contains 99.8 percent of the solar system's total mass. Eight planets orbit this star, along with numerous moons, asteroids, and comets.\n\nThe inner solar system contains four rocky planets. Mercury, closest to the Sun, has extreme temperature swings and no atmosphere. Venus, shrouded in thick clouds of sulfuric acid, is the hottest planet due to runaway greenhouse effect. Earth is the only known planet with liquid water on its surface. Mars, the red planet, shows evidence of ancient rivers and might once have harbored life.\n\nBeyond Mars lies the asteroid belt, a region of rocky debris left over from the solar system's formation. Most asteroids orbit peacefully, but occasionally one strikes Earth. The largest asteroid, Ceres, is now classified as a dwarf planet.\n\nThe outer solar system contains four giant planets. Jupiter, the largest, could fit over 1,300 Earths inside it. Its Great Red Spot is a storm larger than Earth that has raged for centuries. Saturn is famous for its spectacular rings made of ice and rock particles. Uranus rotates on its side, possibly due to an ancient collision. Neptune, the most distant planet, has the strongest winds in the solar system.\n\nPluto was reclassified as a dwarf planet in 2006 after astronomers discovered similar objects in the distant Kuiper Belt. This region beyond Neptune contains thousands of icy bodies, remnants from the solar system's formation.\n\nLight from the Sun takes about 8 minutes to reach Earth but over 4 hours to reach Neptune. Spacecraft have visited all eight planets, sending back stunning images and scientific data. Voyager 1, launched in 1977, has now entered interstellar space, carrying messages from Earth into the cosmos.\n\nScientists continue discovering new objects in our solar system, including potential dwarf planets and mysterious trans-Neptunian objects. Each discovery helps us understand how planetary systems form and evolve.",
