    "orderIndex": 2,
    "content": "Black holes are among the most fascinating and mysterious objects in the universe. These cosmic phenomena possess gravitational pulls so strong that nothing can escape once it crosses their boundary. Even light, the fastest thing in existence, becomes trapped forever within a black hole.\n\nThe concept of black holes dates back to 1783 when English clergyman John Michell first proposed the idea. He imagined stars so massive that their gravity would prevent light from escaping. Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, published in 1915, provided the mathematical framework for understanding these extreme objects. German physicist Karl Schwarzschild calculated the first exact solution to Einstein's equations just months later, describing how space curves around a collapsed star.\n\nBlack holes form when massive stars exhaust their nuclear fuel and collapse under their own gravity. Stars at least 20 times more massive than our Sun can undergo this transformation. The collapse happens rapidly once the star runs out of fuel, crushing matter into an incredibly dense point called a singularity. The boundary beyond which nothing can escape is called the event horizon.\n\nScientists classify black holes into three main categories based on their mass. Stellar black holes contain between 5 and 100 times the mass of our Sun. These form from collapsed stars and may number in the hundreds of millions within our galaxy alone. Supermassive black holes lurk at the centers of most large galaxies, containing millions to billions of solar masses. The black hole at the center of our Milky Way, called Sagittarius A*, contains approximately 4 million solar masses.\n\nIntermediate black holes represent a mysterious middle category that scientists are still working to understand. These objects contain between 100 and 100,000 solar masses. Their formation mechanism remains unclear, though they may result from the merger of smaller black holes over cosmic time scales.\n\nDespite their name, black holes are far from empty voids. Material falling toward a black hole forms a swirling disk of superheated gas called an accretion disk. Friction within this disk heats the material to millions of degrees, causing it to emit powerful X-rays. Some black holes shoot jets of particles outward at nearly the speed of light, stretching across thousands of light-years.\n\nThe Event Horizon Telescope collaboration achieved a historic milestone on April 10, 2019, when they released the first direct image of a black hole. The image showed the supermassive black hole at the center of galaxy M87, located 55 million light-years from Earth. This black hole contains 6.5 billion solar masses and stretches larger than our entire solar system.\n\nTime behaves strangely near black holes due to extreme gravitational effects. An observer watching someone fall into a black hole would see them slow down and appear to freeze at the event horizon. From the falling person's perspective, however, they would cross the horizon in finite time. This difference arises from how gravity warps both space and time together.\n\nStephen Hawking revolutionized our understanding of black holes in 1974 when he proposed that they slowly emit radiation. This Hawking radiation suggests black holes gradually lose mass and could eventually evaporate completely over unimaginably long time scales. A stellar black hole would take longer than the current age of the universe to evaporate. This discovery connected black hole physics with quantum mechanics in surprising ways.\n\nScientists continue studying black holes to understand fundamental questions about gravity, space, and time. Future observations with more powerful telescopes will reveal additional details about these extreme environments. Black holes remain cosmic laboratories where the laws of physics are pushed to their ultimate limits.",
